"Sonogenetics" allows to operate cells of a brain by means of sound waves
On the video it is visible how nematodes change the direction of the movement at the moment when they are affected by sound impulses.
Scientists brought worms with genetically modified nervous system which can be operated, using ispulsa of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change the direction of the movement while influence them sound impulses, too high that the human ear could hear them.
Impulses make impact by activation of the neurons which are genetically modified to use membrane channels which react to ultrasonic waves.
On a subject: Researchers operate brain activity by means of light
Scientists told that worms show possibilities of a new technique under the name "sonogenetics" which essence consists in use of ultrasound for excitement of certain cells of a brain, heart and muscles, at the same time the source of ultrasound settles down out of an organism.
Chalasani's Shrikant, the research associate in Salk Institute, La Jolla, California, told Guardian that this technique could replace deep stimulation of a brain once - the invasive procedure at which electric impulses are sent to a brain of the person and which is used in treatment of a disease of Parkinson.
Hearts nematodes usually do not react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found out that they began to react when they were placed in the liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found out that bubbles strengthen ultrasonic waves which then get into an organism of worms.
The strengthened ultrasonic waves influence the structures called by "ion channels of TRP-4", found in membranes of some cages of worms.
Ultrasonic waves force these ion channels to open and excite cages which are connected with them, is reported in the report in Nature Communications.
For creation of nematodes which can be operated by means of ultrasound Chalasani made genetic modifications of worms so their motor neurons used ion channels of TRP-4.
During application of ultrasound for impact on the modified organisms sound waves amplified microscopic bubbles and were entered into organisms of worms, activating the modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to that which is applied in "optogenetics" - the new direction which allows scientists to switch on and off neurons by means of light impulses.
Chalasani claims that in comparison with this technique sonogenetics can have some advantages.
Unlike light which is delivered to the necessary site of a brain on optical fiber low-frequency ultrasonic waves freely pass through body tissues therefore for their delivery it is not necessary to pass in a cranium.
"We consider that for treatment of some neurologic diseases in clinical conditions use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to make for a while human neurons sensitive to an ultrasonic signal", - Chalasani told.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscular and insulin - to the producing cages.
