Four died when the police opened fire rubber bullets at protesters in Nepal
Four persons, including the 4-year-old boy, were killed in the south of Nepal when the police began firing with rubber bullets in the crowd protesting against the offered new constitution of the country as the official representative on Wednesday declared.
Violence happened in the evening on Tuesday in the District of Rupandehi, approximately in 175 miles to the West from Kathmandu, the capital of the country.
Bishna Prasad Dhakal, the head of district police, reported that more than 1 000 protesters gathered at one of offices of police, some threw stones and fire bombs.
Mr. Dhakal reported that police officers used tear gas, then shot in the air before using rubber bullets.
Twenty employees of police and five civilians were wounded, he told.
It is unclear, why rubber bullets with which, as we know, it is possible to kill however traditionally use them as less killing alternative, caused such high mortality.
This collision was the last for several weeks of fierce protests in the southern, flat part of Nepal where representatives of the Madhesi nationality declare that the new provinces formed under the new constitution will reduce their political influence.
Protests also passed in the west of Nepal, among citizens of nationality a container who want to have the state.
At least, 40 people, including eleven employees of police, were killed in cruel collisions, since 10
August when four main political parties signed the agreement on division of the country into provinces that became a decisive step on the way to the new constitution, however very controversial issue in Nepal which centrally coped throughout several centuries.
Work on the new constitution is conducted since 2008, but legislators accelerated process after a destructive earthquake which claimed the lives of thousands of people in April.
Legislators voted for articles of the draft constitution in Kathmandu this week, and officials declared that new chapter will be signed by Sunday.
