Diabetics with small obesity can be helped by obesity surgery
The favorable effect after obesity surgery at the people with small obesity having diabetes 2 types can last not less than five years, according to a new research.
However now for the present early to claim that diabetics with small obesity live longer after obesity surgery, than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
"The statistics of mortality is shown absolutely not at once", - doctor Robin Blackstone, the expert in obesity surgery who wrote about a new research in a column of the editor of JAMA Surgery declared.
The obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various methods for reduction of the size of a stomach.
They reduce feeling of hunger and limit ability to organiza to acquire food.
For several years the bariatric surgery proved the efficiency for treatment of diabetes 2 types, but the main researches were conducted among the people with morbid obesity having the body weight index (BWI) 35 or above.
BMI, weight concerning growth, is considered normal at value from 18,5 to 24,9.
BMI 25 or says above that the person has an excess weight, and people with BMI higher than 30 reckon as people with obesity.
You can calculate the BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For a new research researchers from the Taiwan hospital Min-Sheng General used the data collected since 2007 for comparison of two types of bariatric surgery - shunting of a stomach and sleeve gastrectomy, with medical treatment of diabetes 2 types at people with small obesity.
The BMI average value at those who underwent surgical intervention fell with 31 to 24,5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in a research.
At the same time BMI at those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains approximately at the level of 29.
Among those who underwent an operation completely recovered from diabetes of 36%, and partially - 28%.
In the group receiving drug treatment for comparison, full treatment from diabetes was observed only at 1%, and partial - only approximately at 2%.
Besides, indicators of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL of cholesterol "in general were better in surgical group", - authors declare.
Researchers also controlled A1s hemoglobin levels in blood which reflect sugar levels in blood in dynamics.
A1c hemoglobin is better to hold lower than 7%, - researchers write.
After surgical intervention the average level of A1c hemoglobin decreased approximately from 9% to about 6%.
In therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, approximately at the level of 8%.
But the best indicators of glycemic control reflected by good levels of A1c hemoglobin did not reduce death rate in five years, according to the head of researches Dr. Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research group also compared average results of two types of surgical treatment.
For the fifth year, in comparison with group, polchivshy sleeve gastrectomy, the group of shunting lost more than the weight (18,7 kg against 14,2 kg), achieved bigger decrease in BMI (on 7,4 against 5,1) and A1s hemoglobin (3,1% against 2,1%), and also was closer to full remission of diabetes (46,9% against 16,7%).
Though the new research does not show advantages of a surgical method regarding life expectancy after five years, there are confirmations by results of a research of people with excess body weight in Sweden that surgical treatment really leads to increase in life expectancy as Blackstone from College of medicine to Phoenix reports, the University of Arizona.
According to the Swedish research for the people with obesity who chose bariatric intervention, probability to die for 15 years was about 29% lower in comparison with group in which more traditional methods were applied.
In spite of the fact that the new research did not show increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it encourages people with BMI lower than 35, interested in such procedure.
"Here the report is very important as it in it is claimed that such surgical intervention is safe in group with low BMI where there is no increased risk of mortality or renal diseases", - she declared.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors have to begin to treat the weight as soon as BMI of the patient gets to range between from 27 to 30 seriously.
"I consider, we too long wait to force people to treat it seriously", - she told.
It seems to me that as soon as they save up genetic changes which start obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is back very difficult to turn it.
