Vesti Economy ― Nobel laureate: globalization
To unpack Processes of globalization had to promote decrease in inequality in the world.
In practice the situation looks differently, the difference, on the contrary, grows in the income of the population in the developing economies.
Eric Maskin.
That to correct it, it is necessary to increase education level of low-skilled workers, the chief researcher of the International laboratory of the analysis and the choice of decisions of Higher School of Economics National Research University, the Nobel Prize laureate on economy considers 2007 Eric Maskin.
In the last twenty years the world endured the unknown growth of the global markets.
Trade borders between the countries became more and more open.
Supporters of globalization predicted big benefits for the developing economies.
"And these forecasts in many respects came true", - Maskin emphasizes.
So, for example, China and India received serious GDP growth per capita.
However not everything is so iridescent.
It was expected that globalization will reduce an abyss between "propertied" and "poor" in the poor countries which is shown in big inequality of incomes, to be exact - compensations.
But actually this inequality only increased, Eric Maskin in the article "Why the Global Markets Did Not Lower Inequality in the Developing Economies" published in The World Bank Economic Review which translated notes and quotes NIE HSE.
Together with the economist, professor of Harvard University Michael Cremer Eric Maskin developed the alternative theory which shows why the difference in the income in the poor countries in process of globalization growth increases, reminds NIE HSE.
In the new global market there are specific processes.
That to show them, Maskin marks out four skill levels of experts - A and B for the rich countries, C and D - for the poor.
After globalization experts of D of the poor countries lack skill level to cooperate with experts of A and B from the rich countries.
And if at workers of level C from the poor countries the salary grows thanks to cooperation with employees of B from the rich, then workers of the D growth do not feel or their salaries fall at all.
Total effect such is that internationalization of production will promote increase in a gap in compensation between two professional categories in the poor countries and according to increase in level of inequality.
Cremer and E. Maskin offered surprisingly beautiful model alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
She allows to explain why globalization led to inequality in the income, - Fuad Aleskerov, ordinary professor, the manager of the International laboratory of the analysis and the choice of decisions, the head of department of mathematics of Higher School of Economics National Research University says.
And as any powerful theory, I am sure, it will lead to surge in empirical works in this area.
The solution, according to Eric Maskin, consists in increase in education level of low-skilled workers.
However workers as the scientist notes, have on it no means, and to the companies is unprofitable to pay their training.
The governments, the international agencies, NPO and private funds can play a significant role in such situation, Maskin considers.
The scientist notes that the developed theory does not call at all for a globalization process stop which bore and bears fruit in the form of GDP growth of the countries.
